<br>
Religion and politics are two very touchy subjects that many people tend to avoid discussing because they are so personal.  Both of these topics have come up in dialog here.<br><br>
I know that my basic religious philosophy changed dramatically because of Vietnam.  My parents told me and I believed what they told me  that the President (as the elected official) was God's representative and if we were at war it had to be God's will.  I now question how we can know whose side God is on when opposing sides claim that status. I am less certain and dogmatic in my beliefs as a result.<br><br>
This is an honest question seeking enlightenment not to  start a debate on whether any particular philosophy or religious belief is correct.  I understand that I am not the only one whose attitutes have changed toward organized religion.  Some people have turned their back on all religions.  Some people have changed their philosophy and follow the oriental philosophy such as one of the Buddisms, or Hinduism.  Some people have found peace in the Indian way of life and thought. <br><br>
How have your attitudes changed toward your basic cultural/religious belief's as a result of your service  in Vietnam?
